  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the best books for organic chemistry?",
  "response": "There are several highly regarded textbooks and resources that can greatly aid in the study of organic chemistry. Here are some of the best books in this field:\n\n1. **\"Organic Chemistry\" by Jonathan Clayden, Nick Greeves, and Stuart Warren** - This book is known for its clear explanations and innovative approach to teaching organic concepts. It includes a variety of problems and is widely used in organic chemistry courses.\n\n2. **\"Organic Chemistry\" by Paula Yurkanis Bruice** - This textbook is appreciated for its accessible writing style and pedagogical approach, emphasizing problem-solving and conceptual understanding.\n\n3. **\"Organic Chemistry\" by Jerry March** - This classic text covers a broad range of topics and provides detailed mechanisms of various reactions. It's suitable for those looking for a more in-depth analysis.\n\n4. **\"Advanced Organic Chemistry\" by Francis A. Carey and Richard J. Sundberg** - This two-volume set is more advanced and is suitable for graduate students. It provides comprehensive coverage of more complex topics in organic chemistry.\n\n5. **\"Organic Chemistry: A Short Course\" by Robert C. Neuman and John E. McGowan** - This book is concise and focuses on key concepts, making it a good option for those who want a more straightforward overview.\n\n6. **\"Organic Chemistry as a Second Language\" by David Klein** - This series (available in two parts) is excellent for reinforcing fundamental concepts and is particularly helpful for exam preparation.\n\n7. **\"Understanding Organic Chemistry\" by Robert J. Ouellette and J. Derek MacLaren** - This book emphasizes the underlying principles of organic chemistry and includes many practice problems.\n\n8. **\"Problem-Solving in Organic Chemistry\" by Joseph Hornback** - This book offers a unique approach by emphasizing problem-solving strategies.\n\n9. **\"Organic Chemistry\" by Wade and Sime** - Another well-structured textbook that provides clear explanations along with numerous examples and practice problems.\n\n10. **\"Greene\u2019s Protective groups in Organic Synthesis\" by Peter G. M. Wuts and Theodora W. Greene** - This is a classic reference for those interested in synthetic organic chemistry and the use of protecting groups.\n\nThese books cover a range of styles and levels of complexity, so it's a good idea to consider what works best for your learning style and what level of depth you need for your coursework or personal interest.",
